node.text:
If all of your debts are paid in full and the accounts are closed, you'll have what's called an "indeterminable" credit score after about 6 months. Then, you'll be able to do what's called "manual underwriting" to buy a home. All that means is that the mortgage company will do what banks used to do all the time when someone bought a home. They'll actually review your finances to check out whether or not you're in a position to pay back the loan.

A mortgage is the only type of debt, I'm okay with. Just make sure that the payment is no more than 25% of your take-home pay on no more than a 15-year mortgage at a fixed rate. I want your house to be a financial blessing in your life, not a financial curse.

You CAN have financial peace. You just need to take your time and do the math to make sure things are done right.

Thanks to Dr. @johndelony for joining me on this call.

#mortgage

There's an addictive thrill that can come with the risk on these sorts of things. Although a lot of people are having a lot of fun with this right now, it's important to not confuse a get-rich-quick scenario with an actual, proven wealth-building plan. Just because a few people won the lottery one time does NOT make it an investment strategy that you should use. If you're debt-free with a full emergency fund, and you want to use some fun/entertainment money that you've budgeted for to play around with these things, I'm not gonna get mad at you, but I don't recommend it… and I certainly don't do this myself. If you REALLY want to play around with single stocks, just make sure that no more than 10% of your net worth is tied up in them. This is to ensure that things don't go overboard to the point that it can actually impact your net worth in a negative way if and when things go south. 

Reminder: I only recommend investing in mutual funds and real estate that's paid for in full. 

#debtfreecommunity

Baby Step #2 of Financial Peace University ✅

In the fall of 2020, my husband, Justin, and I started having serious conversations about our future and how we wanted being debt-free to become a reality for us. We knew we wanted to make a change for our family and for the future of our family.

Justin and I led a Financial Peace University class (second time completing the class for us both) last fall and it was the refresher we needed. We followed a strict budget, cut back on eating out and buying Starbucks, had a yard sale, sold clothes at Plato’s Closet and Uptown Cheapskate, and Justin worked various side gigs to reach our goal of becoming debt-free even sooner.

Getting to pay off our last and final credit card in January 2021 was the motivation we needed to press on with paying off other debts for the next 8 months. The freedom we found with telling our money where to go rather than letting it control us has made for easier conversations in our marriage when it came to finances. It takes dedication, hard work, and patience, but I can promise you that it is worth it in the end.

We are so grateful for God’s direction during this journey. We hope our story can encourage others just as we had dear friends who motivated us through their financial peace journey. We especially thank @daveramsey and the team at Ramsey Solutions in paving the way for our family. If you are looking to take Financial Peace University for the first time or if you are needing a refresher (just like us), Justin and I would love to chat with you.

node.text:
If you're waiting on the government to fix your life, you'll be waiting for a LONG time.

There are some public service career fields that have student loan forgiveness programs. If someone decides to work in those fields for a set amount of time (usually about 10 years), then they would begin to qualify for loan forgiveness if they also meet a huge list of other qualifications.

Sadly, that hasn't been happening. Most people who have worked in these fields and applied for their loans to be forgiven haven't seen a dime of them paid off. 

Even if they had, they were stuck working in a career they didn't necessarily want for a DECADE while still making minimum payments on their loans themselves. I don't want you to stay in debt for another decade! Your life is more valuable than that.

If the government decides to forgive all student loans. Great. They should also stop making the student loans too. In the meantime, work hard in a career of your choosing and pay off your own debt as fast as you can. You'll look back in a decade and be very glad you did. 

#debtfreecommunity
